         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>Restorations are largely those of Robert.</p>
            <p>l. 2, Alternatively: <foreign xml:lang="grc">[ον Ζῆλον τὸν ῥήτορα καὶ σ]οφιστήν</foreign>, Robert; <foreign xml:lang="grc">[ον, Ζήλου υἱὸν, Χαρίδημον σ]οφιστήν</foreign>, Puech</p>
            <p>l. 4, <foreign xml:lang="grc">[ἀρχινεοποιὸν, ἔγγονον ἀρχι]ερέων</foreign> Puech</p>
            <p>l. 4, <foreign xml:lang="grc">[κτίστων, γυμνασιάρχων σ]τεφανη</foreign> Puech</p>
            <p>l. 7, <foreign xml:lang="grc">πάσας</foreign> Cormack, <foreign xml:lang="grc">τὰς μεγίστας</foreign> Puech</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>[?The council and the people honoured ?Julius] Aureli[us Charidemos the] sophist [ priest for life of the God Dio]nysos [...] [descendant of high]priests [and ... -s and those who shared in the found]ing of the [city, having] carried out [?the greatest ] magistracies and lit[urgies hon]ourably [and having ? improved] many [ things ?for the city] [...] money [....]</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>As Robert pointed out, the man honoured may be Julius Aurelius Charidemos Iulianos, known from <ref type="inscription" n="1585" target="120909.xml"/>, or his father Claudius Aurelius Zelos, with a further epithet; both men were sophists.</p>
         </div>
